<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in China (
                        Hurley
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d922</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">922</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-01-12T04:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-01-12T04:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-12T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-12T04:00:00-05:00" n="922" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d922">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5034/1–1245: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-12T16:00:00+07:00">January 12, 1945—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 12—11:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>50. Embassy believes article on registration of auto companies in China December
                    9 issue <hi rend="italic">Foreign Commerce Weekly</hi> substantially correct,
                    but over-simplified. Suggest, with Helmick’s<note n="2" xml:id="d922fn2">Judge
                        Milton J. Helmick, sent to China in November 1944 by the Department of State
                        to survey the effects of Chinese laws, regulations, and courts on American
                        firms having commercial interests in that country.</note> concurrence, that
                    Department advise Commerce to be cautious in advising American companies to
                    register pending hoped-for clarification Chinese company law on subject of
                    qualification and admission of foreign corporations. Will report further.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
